is it true that men can be color blind but women can not hello there no that is not true that women cannot be color blind it just is not as likely for them to have a red green color deficiency compared to men blue yellow color deficiencies affect men and women equally here is some more info on color deficiencies color vision defects are either congenital or acquired while hereditary congenital color defects are almost always red green affecting of males and of females acquired defects are more often of the blue yellow variety and affect males and females equally and can be caused by macular or optic nerve disease most congenital color vision defects affect both eyes equally where as acquired more often affects one eye more then the other congenital defects you are born with and is constant in type and with its severity throughout life acquired color vision defects generally vary in type and severity depending on the location and source of the ocular pathology check out the link for more info Color blindness Color Nystagmus Hypoglycemia Cephalic disorder Congenital disorder Blindness Heterochromia Eye Color vision Retina Glaucoma Melanin Myasthenia gravis Congenital adrenal hyperplasia due to 17 alpha-hydroxylase deficiency Congenital adrenal hyperplasia History of intersex surgery Lipoid congenital adrenal hyperplasia Intersex surgery Optic nerve Folic acid Light-emitting diode Diabetes mellitus Hearing impairment Visual loss Anemia AIDS Multiple sclerosis Light Action potential Diabetic retinopathy Glossary of medical terms related to communications disorders Growth hormone treatment Haemophilia Dog Aphasia Scotoma Herpes simplex virus Floater Retinitis pigmentosa Autoimmune diseases Porphyria Diamond Color theory Benign intracranial hypertension Mental retardation Cryptorchidism Non-Hodgkin's lymphoma Von Willebrand disease Septo-optic dysplasia Androgen insensitivity syndrome Leber's hereditary optic neuropathy Primary color CIE 1931 color space Noonan syndrome T